  <ns3:title xmlns:ns3="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">FS-TD-003/3.2.4/Validate penalty calculation logic - compound interest calculation.</ns3:title>
  <ns3:description xmlns:ns3="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">At the account level, when penalty calculation logic is set to compound interest then the following calculation must take place: 

Penalty Amount = [{Amount x (1 + R/365) ^n} – Amount] 

Where r = interest rate % and n = number of penalty days

In case of Partial redemption, Amount = (Redemption amount – Capitalized Unpaid Interest)

In case of Full redemption, Amount = (Current balance – Capitalized Unpaid Interest)

For example, let us take the case of $50,000 partial redemption from a term deposit account where the capitalized unpaid interest is zero. The rate of interest is 1% and the interest penalty is 60 days. 

Penalty amount           = 50,000 x (1 + 0.01/365) ^60

                              = 50,000 x (1.000027397) ^60 = 50082.26
•    Penalty = (50082.26 – 50000) = $82.26


Success Criteria: Penalty amount is $82.26</ns3:description>
